column23: I was very new to programming so this was a way for me to be introduced (together with "into to r"). I found the real time discussion of problem solving extremely useful - it enable me to see how people familiar with R would work their way through a new problem, and to recognise that this is common to everyone using the program. It also enabled me to see the resources they used to trouble shoot and the way they would frame problems to think about them (all of which are very difficult to ascertain when you're reading a document). Documented materials are helpful when you have a good feel for what you're doing and want to stretch your wings, but I think live is invaluable (and vastly more efficient) when you're starting out or embarking on a new realm of understanding. It's like evolution of learning in action.
column25: I think the structure of the live courses with live support, open discussion and an entirely supportive and non-judgemental approach is fantastic. I've been impressed by the really helpful attitude of all the tutors to facilitate learning. Great system - I rave about intersect in general to people! In particular, I encourage medical colleagues to use intersect courses to learn R, as there is little "in house" familiarity with R at the moment within the medical (non-academic research) community and I think this is an opportunity lost in terms of clinical research / time efficiency as many doctors undertake some form of research during their training but often without supported research infrastructure. Thank you!
